Installation of Git
---
Windows : Download and Install git from git-scm.com
1. Download Git from:
   https://git-scm.com/
2. Run the installer and follow the installation steps.
3. Verify the installation:
   - Open Command Prompt (Windows) or Terminal (Linux/macOS).
   - Run the command:
     git --version
    This should display the Git version if installed correctly.

Linux : yum install git -y
       check git --version
---

Step 2: Set Up Git with Your Name and Email
1. Open Command Prompt (Windows) or Terminal (Linux/macOS).
2. Configure Git with your name and email:
   Run the following commands:
   git config --global user.name "Your Name"
   git config --global user.email "your-email@example.com"
   To identify who committed the code.
3. Verify the configuration:
   Run:
   git config --global --list
   This will display your settings.

---
Step 3: Install GitHub Desktop (Optional)
1. Go to:
   https://desktop.github.com/
2. Download and install GitHub Desktop for your operating system.
3. Follow the on-screen instructions to log in with your GitHub account.
---

2 Ways to commit code
1st Method: Clone an Existing GitHub Repository
1. Set Up a GitHub Account
  Visit: https://github.com/
2. Click "Sign up" and enter your username, email, and password.
3. Verify your email address.
4.Log in to your GitHub account.
5.Create Your First GitHub Repository
6.Click "New" to create a new repository.
7.Enter the repository name, select either "Private" and click "Create repository."
8.Open cmd or gitbash enter this command
  git clone https://github.com/username/repository.git
  cd repostitoryname
  modify files
  git status -s
  git add .
  git status -s
  git commit -a -m "Added files "
  git push (Here it prompts for authentication )



---

2nd method : Connect Your Local Project to GitHub

1. Open Command Prompt or Terminal in your local project folder.
2. Run the following commands:
   mkdir my_project
   cd my_project
   git init
   Create files A.txt B.txt
   git status -s
   git add .
   git status -s
   git commit -a -m "Added files "
   git remote add origin https://github.com/your-username/repo-name.git
   git push -u origin master



---

Step 7: Verify Your Code on GitHub
1. Go to your repository on GitHub.
2. Your files should now appear in the repository.

---
